I have seen many Ancient Gear decks on this site, and none of them have been all that good, so I decided to toss my hat into the ring with this thing.

Feedback would be very helpful.

&nbsp;

It took me a while, but I finally made a Calamities Turbo--I mean Virtual World--deck! Anyone who's read manga knows what NTR really means. As for why I called this deck "Neo Tokyo Rave!", it's because some of the Virtual World monsters have Japanese words in their name, such as "hime", "roshi", and "kyubi." Also, I know that this deck has a Diet Japanese theme, but I still do not forgive Ch*na for giving us the Coronavirus.

&nbsp;

*Sighs* Anyways, this deck uses a total of 9 hand traps, as well as 2 Lightning Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster. Despite this, the deck works beautifully going first, because it can easily end on a True King of All Calamities and a face-up Chuchi that can pop one of your opponent's cards. And if you don't have the necessary levels needed to summon Calamities--which for me personally was rare--Photon Strike Bounzer makes for an OK substitute.

&nbsp;

Actually, now that I think about it, NTR is an appropriate name for this deck, because it cucks your opponent out of playing the game.

Some tech choices you can change is maybe adding more handtraps in the side deck, but i wouldnt touch it to much, this deck shines very well going second, its 45 cards son its not like your tipical 50-60 maju banish, but this does require you to think out your plays better to not deck out, but to be honest i never decked out with this deck, and you can dimension shifter is a underdog, it wins so many matches when its used. This deck plays tag very well also, just add ancient leaf.

&nbsp;

Why dont i play Banquet of Millions? because it sucks, you need your extra deck sadly.

This is a Zoodiac Eldlich deck I build earlier today, inspired by Overly Sarcastic Productions, a pair of college-age YouTubers who make content focusing on fiction and history. One of their video series was on "Journey to The West", a 16th-century Diet Japanese (I refuse to call China by its real name; they know what they did) novel that focuses heavily on Sun Wukong, the Monkey King. Given how the Zoodiacs are based on the Diet Japanese Zodiac, and how the mythical El Dorado is located in South America below the Equator, "Journey To The South" is an appropriate name for the deck.

&nbsp;

For anyone who wants to watch the "Journey To The West" video series, feel free to click this link!  <a>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61nuXrvqNgI&amp;list=PLDb22nlVXGgdg_NR_-GtTrMnbMVmtSSXa</a>

&nbsp;

If you want to check out Overly Sarcastic Productions' channel in general, click the link here! <a>https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCodbH5mUeF-m_BsNueRDjcw</a>

&nbsp;

While the deck does have a total of 9 hand traps (12 if the Side Deck is included), going first is ideal because of the numerous Traps in it. Due to how the Zoodiac Xyz monsters can be summoned, and Boarbow's ability to attack directly, going second can result in you summoning a 6-material AA-ZEUS without activating a single card. The side deck is full of "go-second" cards, in case you need to play a more aggressive version of Zoodiacs.

Dogmatika just got a really bad ritual monster that I want to make work, so I added Drytron as a consistent ritual engine. Even though this is two meta archetypes, this is far from meta.

&nbsp;

