Fossil is an archetype I've been meaning to touch upon for a few months, but because I'm a lazy fool, it took me until almost Christmas 2020 to make a deck! For those of you who loved Nintendo's games, or have an autism-induced obsession with prehistoric life, this deck was named after the Fossil Fighters franchise. I actually got the first game when I was in my pre-teens, and I would play that crap for hours. HOURS spent digging up bones (and some fossilized droppings), cleaning them, and just slapping together teams of superpowered dinos. I also got Fossil Fighters: Champions, which was also a great game I got hooked on!

&nbsp;

Anyways, this Fossil deck also uses a small Adamancipator engine, and for good reason. One of Fossil's newest support cards was Flint Cragger, which lets you discard a card and send one of their Fusion monsters from your Extra Deck to the Graveyard. And because most of them have Graveyard effects that either add cards to your hand or pop your opponent's card, losing that card in your hand isn't a big deal. So Flint Cragger works amazingly with the "Adamancipator" Tuners, since they can summon Rock non-Tuners from your deck.

&nbsp;

Because Fossil is basically the Rock equivalent of Cyber Dragons, this deck has to go second every single time. With 9 hand traps, 2 Lightning Storm, and Harpie's Feather Duster, stopping your opponent from making any significant plays is top priority. Then on your turn, your goal is to try and get Fossil Fusion to your hand and OTK your opponent! And because Konami is too stupid to ban Halqifibrax, you can use Cross-Sheep to link climb into it, then use Halq's effect to go into Selene, and finally Accesscode Talker.

&nbsp;

But if you need to go first, there is some hope for you. Due to Halq and Cross-Sheep making great extenders, you can use them going first to put two Link 2s on board, and use them to make Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. But because the Extra Deck is so tight, I couldn't put Masquerena in there. Ugh...
